>[Question]
>hi,
>doc, can u help me with this problem
>
>If    x    =   y    =   z  
>     ----    -----     ------
>     a-b      b-c     c-a
>
>
>show that x+y+z=0...
>   
>
>[Difficulty]
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>

Thanks for writing to Ask Dr. Math, Kevin!

Put r = x/(a-b), so x = r*(a-b).  Do similarly for the other
fractions in the first equation(s).  Then compute x + y + z in terms
of r, a, b, and c, and see that it equals zero.

Feel free to reply if I can help further with this question.


